When an agent hallucates a CLI path or gets an error, the
interface is wrong, not the agent. Fix the interface.

Story: an agent tried eval $(mycelium.sh branch use jj-support) and
the env var died between shell invocations. The agent did the right
thing — the tool's design assumed interactive shells. We added
.git/mycelium-branch file persistence so branch selection survives
across invocations. Then the agent tried refs/notes/mycelium/jj-support
and hit a git limitation: refs can't be both a leaf and a directory.
We changed to mycelium--jj-support. Two fixes, both from listening to
what the agent naturally tried to do.

(Term from Steve Yegge: desire paths are the trails people wear
through grass when the sidewalk doesn't go where they need.)
